ISRAEL’S DRUZE POLICY AND DISMANTLING OF SYRIA [3]
NETANYAHU IS EXPLOITING THE WEAKNESS OF THE DAMASCUS REGIME AND ITS LACK OF CONTROL OVER LARGE AREAS OF THE COUNTRY.
BY: HILAL KHASHAN
Since the fall of Bashar Assad’s regime last December, Israel has carried out more than 500 airstrikes to prevent the former regime's weapons from reaching the new Syrian authorities, whom it
describes as jihadists. Israel also took control of the demilitarized zone in the Syrian Golan Heights, including the strategic summit of Mount Hermon. In southern Syria, Israeli forces have advanced
to less than 20 kilometers (12.5 miles) from the derelict Mezzeh air base, southeast of Damascus' old sector. The Israeli military said it was deployed in southern Syria to prevent enemy forces from
entering areas inhabited by the Druze minority. Defense Minister Israel Katz threatened more than two months ago to intervene militarily if the new Syrian government harmed the Druze, who comprise 3
percent of Syria’s population (and about half that share of the Israeli population).
This commitment was put to the test at the end of April, when sectarian clashes erupted in the suburbs of Damascus after an audio recording attributed to a Druze man surfaced online that included
insults of the Prophet Muhammad. Israel responded with what officials described as cautionary strikes against government security forces in a mostly Druze town on the capital’s outskirts. The
sectarian violence largely ended a short time later, having left more than 100 dead in two days. Nevertheless, two days later, Israeli warplanes conducted massive airstrikes against Syrian military
targets, including an area adjacent to the presidential palace in Damascus. Announcing the strikes, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu reiterated his pledge to protect the Druze community.
The Israeli claim to defend the Druze seems to conceal a deeper agenda aimed at redrawing the Syrian map, part of Netanyahu’s vow on Oct. 8, 2023, to transform the Middle East. Hours before the more
recent Israeli bombing, Druze religious authorities and military factions rejected secession and affirmed that they are an integral part of Syria. They also endorsed the government’s activation of
the Interior Ministry and judicial police in Sweida province, a stronghold of the Druze community, to ensure public security and stability. Sweida’s governor confirmed their appeals for civil peace
and rejection of violence.
SEEING BEYOND THE DRUZE
Israel seems to be operating under the assumption that dismantling Syria – which Israel’s finance minister listed as one of the country’s goals several days before the belated bombing – would
shield Israel from its adversaries, ending the more than century-old conflict with Arabs. Netanyahu also fears that inaction would leave Syria’s fate to be decided by Turkey, a key ally of the new
Syrian regime, but wants to avoid a direct conflict with Ankara.
