Israel is exploiting the weakness of the Syrian regime and its lack of control over large areas, including the Alawite-dominated coast, regions controlled by Turkey and the Kurds in the north, and the
Bedouin areas in the southeast. It is operating in southern Syria because this region is not a priority for Damascus at the moment, enabling Israel to impose a new reality on the ground. Eventually,
it hopes to encourage the Alawites and Ismailis, not to mention the Kurds, to form their own entities as part of Netanyahu's plan to remake the region.
Israel’s long-standing involvement with the Druze community, dating to the country’s formation in 1948, supports this endeavor. Israel believes it can foster a separatist Druze identity within
Syria with the help of Druze Israeli leaders, given their ability to communicate directly with the Druze in Syria. By emphasizing the blood alliance between the Jewish state and the Druze, Israel
seeks to consolidate its permanent presence in southern Syria.
TERRORISM CHARGE
Israel’s opportunity to intervene directly in Syria came immediately after the collapse of Assad’s regime in December. As part of its effort to undermine the new government in Damascus, Netanyahu
has repeatedly accused Syria’s president, Ahmed al-Sharaa, of leading terrorist organizations bent on Israel’s destruction. But although al-Sharaa’s former group, Hayat Tahrir al-Sham, is a
jihadist movement, its ambitions are not transnational – as Israel well knows.
The 1967 Six-Day War served as a watershed in the ideological orientation of Islamic jihadism. Before the war, transnational movements such as the Muslim Brotherhood and the Islamic Liberation Party
operated in many Arab and Muslim countries with the goal of resurrecting the caliphate state, which was dismantled after the Ottoman Empire's collapse in 1918. After the 1967 war, emerging Islamic
movements focused on the near enemy – i.e., the corrupt national political system – aiming to topple it and build a sharia-guided political system in its ruins. (Al-Qaida was probably the only
exception. Osama bin Laden turned against the U.S. after the 1990 Gulf War. It was not that bin Laden supported Iraq's invasion of Kuwait – he proposed forming an Islamic army to drive out the
Iraqis and reinstate Kuwait's independence – but he viewed the stationing of more than half a million U.S. troops in Saudi Arabia as an insult to the Islamic purity of the Arabian Peninsula.)
“Hayat Tahrir al-Sham” translates as “Organization for the Liberation of Greater Syria.” It never targeted Israel or Western interests. In fact, Israel used to treat its wounded in southwest
Syria before its expulsion and confinement to Idlib in northwestern Syria in 2016. Even the Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant (a reference to Greater Syria) had no interest in targeting Israel,
preferring instead to focus on the Syrian government and competing Islamic movements.
SYRIA'S IDENTITY CRISIS
Although they now lead the government in Damascus, the “liberation” of the Levant remains the end goal for al-Sharaa and his comrades. Geographically and demographically, Syria and Iraq form a
single unit – the Fertile Crescent. They were united from the dawn of history until Britain and France carved the region into areas of influence with the Sykes-Picot Agreement of 1916, with the
former claiming Iraq, Palestine and Transjordan and the latter Syria and Lebanon. This division, formalized by the 1920 San Remo Conference, was arbitrary and illogical, intended to shatter the hopes
of the region’s inhabitants of forming a modern state.
Arabs in both Syria and Iraq opposed the arrangement. In 1919, Faisal bin Hussein, leader of the Arab delegation to the Paris Peace Conference, rejected the Treaty of Versailles and demanded the
implementation of the King-Crane Commission’s recommendations. Authorized by U.S. President Woodrow Wilson to survey local opinion, the commission called for establishing an Arab state in Greater
Syria and restricting Jewish immigration to Palestine, citing Arabs’ categorical rejection of a Jewish state in Palestine.
In March 1920, the Syrian National Congress declared the birth of the Arab Kingdom of Syria and appointed Faisal as its king. His Advisory Council in Damascus included members from all of Syria's
natural regions as well as Iraq, such as Nuri Pasha al-Said, Taha Pasha al-Hashimi and Yassin Pasha al-Hashimi. However, four months later, French forces defeated his army at the Battle of Maysalun.
Faisal fled to London, and in 1921 the British installed him as king of Iraq.
Immediately after his coronation, King Faisal I adopted a rigorous pan-Arab policy that extended beyond West Asia to include Egypt and the Maghreb region. He entrusted Sati al-Husri, whom he appointed
minister of education, to formulate a doctrine of Arab nationalism. He also sought to unite Syria and Iraq, but Britain and France blocked all attempts until his death in 1933. His son Ghazi succeeded
him. A staunch pan-Arabist, King Ghazi drew close to Germany, which gifted him a radio station that he used to broadcast anti-British political commentaries and promote unification between Iraq and
Syria. Alarmed by the threat to British interests, Ambassador Maurice Patterson urged Britain to control or depose him. On April 4, 1939, the Iraqi government announced Ghazi’s death in a car
accident, though many Iraqis believe the British orchestrated his killing.
In the 1940s and 1950s, unity between Iraq and the Levant was a pivotal issue for both domestic politics and the region. After Egypt signed the Camp David Accords in 1978, the Baathist regimes in
Syria and Iraq attempted to unify. However, their presidents – both of whom hailed from the ruling minority sects in their respective countries (Sunni Saddam Hussein and Alawite Hafez Assad) –
pursued narrow personal politics that derailed talks. Nevertheless, the dream of a united Iraq and Syria resides permanently in the collective consciousness of most Iraqis and Syrians.
ISRAEL’S DILEMMA
When Theodor Herzl published “The Jewish State” pamphlet in 1896, advocating a sovereign Jewish homeland to protect Jews from European antisemitism and rejection, he viewed Palestine as the ideal
place to ensure the Jewish people's security. Frequent attacks on Jewish immigrants by Palestinians led Zeev Jabotinsky and Eliyahu Golomb to establish the Haganah, a Jewish self-defense organization
in 1920. The following year, large-scale anti-Jewish riots in Jaffa initiated a spate of mutual violence that still has not subsided, even after the founding of the Jewish state in May 1948. The fact
that Israel has not enjoyed security after more than three-quarters of a century of existence raises fundamental questions that lie outside the scope of this essay.
The day after Hamas launched its massive Oct. 7 attack, Netanyahu said Israel would transform the Middle East by the time the war ends. However, there is no guarantee that such a transformation will
enhance Israel's security. Israel's present approach to regional peace assumes that resolution must be zero-sum and that Israel has won, but for Arabs – just as much as for Israelis – this is a
battle of identities. In such a conflict, victory is elusive even in the long run.
