<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Israel is exploiti=
ng the weakness of the Syrian regime and its lack of control over large are=
as, including the Alawite-dominated coast, regions controlled by Turkey and=
 the Kurds in the north, and the Bedouin areas in the southeast. It is oper=
ating in southern Syria because this region is not a priority for Damascus =
at the moment, enabling Israel to impose a new reality on the ground. Event=
ually, it hopes to encourage the Alawites and Ismailis, not to mention the =
Kurds, to form their own entities as part of Netanyahu's plan to remake the=
 region.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Israel=E2=80=99s l=
ong-standing involvement with the Druze community, dating to the country=E2=
=80=99s formation in 1948, supports this endeavor. Israel believes it can f=
oster a separatist Druze identity within Syria with the help of Druze Israe=
li leaders, given their ability to communicate directly with the Druze in S=
yria. By emphasizing the blood alliance between the Jewish state and the Dr=
uze, Israel seeks to consolidate its permanent presence in southern Syria.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>Terrorism =
Charge</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Israel=E2=80=99s o=
pportunity to intervene directly in Syria came immediately after the collap=
se of Assad=E2=80=99s regime in December. As part of its effort to undermin=
e the new government in Damascus, Netanyahu has repeatedly accused Syria=E2=
=80=99s president, Ahmed al-Sharaa, of leading terrorist organizations bent=
 on Israel=E2=80=99s destruction. But although al-Sharaa=E2=80=99s former g=
roup, Hayat Tahrir al-Sham, is a jihadist movement, its ambitions are not t=
ransnational =E2=80=93 as Israel well knows.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The 1967 Six-Day W=
ar served as a watershed in the ideological orientation of Islamic jihadism=
. Before the war, transnational movements such as the Muslim Brotherhood an=
d the Islamic Liberation Party operated in many Arab and Muslim countries w=
ith the goal of resurrecting the caliphate state, which was dismantled afte=
r the Ottoman Empire's collapse in 1918. After the 1967 war, emerging Islam=
ic movements focused on the near enemy =E2=80=93 i.e., the corrupt national=
 political system =E2=80=93 aiming to topple it and build a sharia-guided p=
olitical system in its ruins. (Al-Qaida was probably the only exception. Os=
ama bin Laden turned against the U.S. after the 1990 Gulf War. It was not t=
hat bin Laden supported Iraq's invasion of Kuwait =E2=80=93 he proposed for=
ming an Islamic army to drive out the Iraqis and reinstate Kuwait's indepen=
dence =E2=80=93 but he viewed the stationing of more than half a million U.=
S. troops in Saudi Arabia as an insult to the Islamic purity of the Arabian=
 Peninsula.)</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">=E2=80=9CHayat Tah=
rir al-Sham=E2=80=9D translates as =E2=80=9COrganization for the Liberation=
 of Greater Syria.=E2=80=9D It never targeted Israel or Western interests. =
In fact, Israel used to treat its wounded in southwest Syria before its exp=
ulsion and confinement to Idlib in northwestern Syria in 2016. Even the Isl=
amic State in Iraq and the Levant (a reference to Greater Syria) had no int=
erest in targeting Israel, preferring instead to focus on the Syrian govern=
ment and competing Islamic movements.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>Syria's Id=
entity Crisis</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Although they now =
lead the government in Damascus, the =E2=80=9Cliberation=E2=80=9D of the Le=
vant remains the end goal for al-Sharaa and his comrades. Geographically an=
d demographically, Syria and Iraq form a single unit =E2=80=93 the Fertile =
Crescent. They were united from the dawn of history until Britain and Franc=
e carved the region into areas of influence with the Sykes-Picot Agreement =
of 1916, with the former claiming Iraq, Palestine and Transjordan and the l=
atter Syria and Lebanon. This division, formalized by the 1920 San Remo Con=
ference, was arbitrary and illogical, intended to shatter the hopes of the =
region=E2=80=99s inhabitants of forming a modern state.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Arabs in both Syri=
a and Iraq opposed the arrangement. In 1919, Faisal bin Hussein, leader of =
the Arab delegation to the Paris Peace Conference, rejected the Treaty of V=
ersailles and demanded the implementation of the King-Crane Commission=E2=
=80=99s recommendations. Authorized by U.S. President Woodrow Wilson to sur=
vey local opinion, the commission called for establishing an Arab state in =
Greater Syria and restricting Jewish immigration to Palestine, citing Arabs=
=E2=80=99 categorical rejection of a Jewish state in Palestine.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In March 1920, the=
 Syrian National Congress declared the birth of the Arab Kingdom of Syria a=
nd appointed Faisal as its king. His Advisory Council in Damascus included =
members from all of Syria's natural regions as well as Iraq, such as Nuri P=
asha al-Said, Taha Pasha al-Hashimi and Yassin Pasha al-Hashimi. However, f=
our months later, French forces defeated his army at the Battle of Maysalun=
. Faisal fled to London, and in 1921 the British installed him as king of I=
raq.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">Immediately after =
his coronation, King Faisal I adopted a rigorous pan-Arab policy that exten=
ded beyond West Asia to include Egypt and the Maghreb region. He entrusted =
Sati al-Husri, whom he appointed minister of education, to formulate a doct=
rine of Arab nationalism. He also sought to unite Syria and Iraq, but Brita=
in and France blocked all attempts until his death in 1933. His son Ghazi s=
ucceeded him. A staunch pan-Arabist, King Ghazi drew close to Germany, whic=
h gifted him a radio station that he used to broadcast anti-British politic=
al commentaries and promote unification between Iraq and Syria. Alarmed by =
the threat to British interests, Ambassador Maurice Patterson urged Britain=
 to control or depose him. On April 4, 1939, the Iraqi government announced=
 Ghazi=E2=80=99s death in a car accident, though many Iraqis believe the Br=
itish orchestrated his killing.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">In the 1940s and 1=
950s, unity between Iraq and the Levant was a pivotal issue for both domest=
ic politics and the region. After Egypt signed the Camp David Accords in 19=
78, the Baathist regimes in Syria and Iraq attempted to unify. However, the=
ir presidents =E2=80=93 both of whom hailed from the ruling minority sects =
in their respective countries (Sunni Saddam Hussein and Alawite Hafez Assad=
) =E2=80=93 pursued narrow personal politics that derailed talks. Neverthel=
ess, the dream of a united Iraq and Syria resides permanently in the collec=
tive consciousness of most Iraqis and Syrians.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0"><strong>Israel=E2=
=80=99s Dilemma</strong></p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">When Theodor Herzl=
 published =E2=80=9CThe Jewish State=E2=80=9D pamphlet in 1896, advocating =
a sovereign Jewish homeland to protect Jews from European antisemitism and =
rejection, he viewed Palestine as the ideal place to ensure the Jewish peop=
le's security. Frequent attacks on Jewish immigrants by Palestinians led Ze=
ev Jabotinsky and Eliyahu Golomb to establish the Haganah, a Jewish self-de=
fense organization in 1920. The following year, large-scale anti-Jewish rio=
ts in Jaffa initiated a spate of mutual violence that still has not subside=
d, even after the founding of the Jewish state in May 1948. The fact that I=
srael has not enjoyed security after more than three-quarters of a century =
of existence raises fundamental questions that lie outside the scope of thi=
s essay.</p>
<p style=3D"line-height:24px;color:#2A3034;margin:1em 0">The day after Hama=
s launched its massive Oct. 7 attack, Netanyahu said Israel would transform=
 the Middle East by the time the war ends. However, there is no guarantee t=
hat such a transformation will enhance Israel's security. Israel's present =
approach to regional peace assumes that resolution must be zero-sum and tha=
t Israel has won, but for Arabs =E2=80=93 just as much as for Israelis =E2=
=80=93 this is a battle of identities. In such a conflict, victory is elusi=
ve even in the long run.</p>

